07824nam a22009855i 9780812204360DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20112011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979753969  a97808122043607 a10.9783/97808122043602doi  a(DE-B1597)463537  a(OCoLC)794925510  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPN842b.M63 2011 7aLIT0042102bisacsh04a809/.8892422200aModern Jewish Literatures :bIntersections and Boundaries /ced. by Sheila E. Jelen, Michael P. Kramer, L. Scott Lerner. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b9 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJewish Culture and Contexts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Intersections and Boundaries in Modern Jewish Literary Study -- tChapter 1. Literary Culture and Jewish Space around 1800: The Berlin Salons Revisited -- tChapter 2. Joseph Salvador’s Jerusalem Lost and Jerusalem Regained -- tChapter 3. The Merchant at the Threshold: Rashel Khin, Osip Mandelstam, and the Poetics of Apostasy -- tChapter 4. Shmuel Saadi Halevy/Sam Lévy Between Ladino and French: Reconstructing a Writer’s Social Identity -- tChapter 5. I. L. Peretz’s ‘‘Between Two Mountains’’: Neo-Hasidism and Jewish Literary Modernity -- tChapter 6. Neither Here nor There: The Critique of Ideological Progress in Sholem Aleichem’s Kasrilevke Stories -- tChapter 7. Brenner: Between Hebrew and Yiddish -- tChapter 8. Eisig Silberschlag and the Persistence of the Erotic in American Hebrew Poetry -- tChapter 9. The Art of Sex in Yiddish Poems: Celia Dropkin and Her Contemporaries -- tChapter 10. Ethnopoetics in the Works of Malkah Shapiro and Ita Kalish: Gender, Popular Ethnography, and the Literary Face of Jewish Eastern Europe -- tChapter 11. Eternal Jews and Dead Dogs: The Diasporic Other in Natan Alterman’s The Seventh Column -- tChapter 12. Inserted Notes: David Boder’s DP Interview Project and the Languages of the Holocaust -- tChapter 13. Unpacking My Father’s Bookstore -- tChapter 14. The Art of Assimilation: Ironies, Ambiguities, Aesthetics -- tChapter 15. Hebraism and Yiddishism: Paradigms of Modern Jewish Literary History -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIs there such a thing as a distinctive Jewish literature? While definitions have been offered, none has been universally accepted. Modern Jewish literature lacks the basic markers of national literatures: it has neither a common geography nor a shared language—though works in Hebrew or Yiddish are almost certainly included—and the field is so diverse that it cannot be contained within the bounds of one literary category.Each of the fifteen essays collected in Modern Jewish Literatures takes on the above question by describing a movement across boundaries—between languages, cultures, genres, or spaces. Works in Hebrew and Yiddish are amply represented, but works in English, French, German, Italian, Ladino, and Russian are also considered. Topics range from the poetry of the Israeli nationalist Natan Alterman to the Russian poet Osip Mandelstam; from turn-of-the-century Ottoman Jewish journalism to wire-recorded Holocaust testimonies; from the intellectual salons of late eighteenth-century Berlin to the shelves of a Jewish bookstore in twentieth-century Los Angeles.The literary world described in Modern Jewish Literatures is demarcated chronologically by the Enlightenment, the Haskalah, and the French Revolution, on one end, and the fiftieth anniversary of the State of Israel on the other. The particular terms of the encounter between a Jewish past and present for modern Jews has varied greatly, by continent, country, or village, by language, and by social standing, among other things. What unites the subjects of these studies is not a common ethnic, religious, or cultural history but rather a shared endeavor to use literary production and writing in general as the laboratory in which to explore and represent Jewish experience in the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aHebrew literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aJewish literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aJews in literature. 0aJewsxIdentity. 0aJudaism and literature. 0aJudaism in literature. 0aYiddish literaturexHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aJewish Studies.  aLiterature.1 aBorovaya, Olga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaplan, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlaser, Amelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHellerstein, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJelen, Sheila E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJelen, Sheila E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKramer, Michael P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKramer, Michael P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLerner, L. Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLerner, L. Scott, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMintz, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNevo, Gideon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNorich, Anita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosen, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoss, Nicham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoth, Laurence, econtributor.